  	    "description": "The GQ Style Guy answers questions on peak lapels, Tom Ford\u0027s secret style moves, and kids who dress better than you.",
  	    "articleBody": "I love the wider peak lapels on suit jackets that I\u0027m seeing everywhere lately—but I have narrow shoulders. Can I pull off a blazer like that even if I\u0027m crazy thin?[Holds fist in the air in solidarity] We scrawny fellows don\u0027t always have it easy. I have two or three wide-lapel blazers and suit jackets, so I\u0027m for the look. But there are some that just don\u0027t work with the Reggie Miller body type. I know now that if I try on the jacket and the lapels look more like wings sprouting from my chest, I move on. The worst thing you can do is buy the jacket and hope it grows on you. (The second-worst thing: asking a tailor to slim the lapels, which never works.) Good style is like batting. Knowing which pitches not to swing at is half the battle. \u000A\u000A\u000A\u000AFacebookPinterestGetty Images\u000A\u000AHow does Tom Ford get his shirt plackets so stiff? I like the look of leaving 2 or 3 buttons un-done, but my shirt always slouches. How do I get my plackets to look crisp?If every American man spent at least an hour a week asking how the hell Tom Ford looks so good, we\u0027d be the world\u0027s best-dressed nation. We\u0027ve tried to steal Mr. Ford\u0027s style secrets before, but I don\u0027t think he covered perfect shirt plackets. I can tell you how he doesn\u0027t do it—or at least how you shouldn\u0027t: by using starch. That\u0027s like injecting poison into your beautiful shirt. You have two options to get that off-duty-millionaire-playboy-open-shirt look. Option A: find a shirt with a stiff, substantial collar—the thicker, the better. That\u0027ll hold up the shirt, and let it cascade out of your lapels. Try it on in the store with your favorite blazer. Option B: If you want the Tom Ford look, splash out on a Tom Ford shirt. He is your cocktail hour spirit guide after all, right?\u000A\u000A\u000A\u000AI try not to repeat outfits on Instagram. Is that silly?Yes.\u000A\u000A\u000A\u000AFacebookPinterestGetty Images\u000A\u000AMy coworker has a five-year-old son that he\u0027s constantly dressing like a tiny street-style star. I think it\u0027s annoying and damaging to the child. What do you think?I get what you\u0027re feeling—let a kid just be a kid. Living in N.Y.C., it\u0027s common to walk through SoHo and see a toddler wearing shoes that cost more mine. I get a little jealous, I\u0027ll admit. Then I check myself. I don\u0027t have any little StyleBabies at the moment, but if I did, I\u0027d teach \u0027em everything I know. And part of that would be lessons on style. If a dad can teach his little guy what sports teams to root for and what music is good, why can\u0027t he teach him how to dress? (Also: you\u0027re hating on a five-year-old. Maybe the problem isn\u0027t that he dresses so well, but that you got out-shined by a five-year-old?)",
  	    "author": ["Mark Anthony Green"],
  	    "keywords": ["Instagram","Style Guy","Suits","Tom Ford"]
